# Tide O Meter

# Introduction

This project was conceived after I made a [web page](https://delongiot.com/tides.html) to display the state of the tide in Punta Mita as follows:   
![][image1]  
It gives a quick glance into the existing tide state. As the “clock pointer” moves around, the state of the tide is visually represented. It does not represent the absolute height of the tide but where the tide is in its phase (high-low, low-high) is obvious. In this example, it is ¾ the way to low tide from the previous high tide. 

It has morphed into a physical implementation that I call the TideOMeter  
![][image2]  
I removed the guts of a dead clock and replaced it with a microcomputer, stepper motor, controller and a battery (to survive brief outages) all hot-glued onto the back. Melissa painted the faceplate adding sand to the bottom to represent the beach (low tide). I found a stick on the beach and carved it into a rustic pointer.  

# Hardware

## Processor

The ESP32 platform is awesome. It has plenty of flash, RAM and I/O for just about all my projects. Couple that with its built-in WiFi and it becomes a great Internet-of-Things. I used an older Sparkfun ESP32 Thing from the junkbox. It is fine but I am preferring the [ESP32 Thing Plus](https://www.sparkfun.com/products/24408) for newer projects. It has a ton more flash, [Qwiic](https://www.sparkfun.com/qwiic) interface and a SD card slot for virtually unlimited storage. 

## Stepper Motor

I bought the [stepper motor](https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00W8XJ6RK) and [controller](https://www.amazon.com.mx/dp/B09MJ4XPXD) from Amazon. The controller uses 7 GPIO lines. I run the motor on USB (5V) power and utilize PWM to reduce power consumption. 

### Phase

The stepper goes through 4 phases as it moves around. Each phase transition is a 0.9 degree step. There are 400 steps/rotation in total. It seems the stepper likes to land on a certain phase and will jump there if unpowered. I think this is due to residual magnetism. 

### Feedback

There is no feedback as to where the motor is positioned. However, it seems to do a good job going to the correct position after initializing the position and keeping track of steps. 

# Software

The software is written in the Arduino IDE. Arduino has its quirks but is generally a quick, easy way to develop. [Here is the source on github](https://github.com/limerickcabin/TideOMeter) 

## Tide Data

The tide data is retrieved from the internet using an API from [worldtides.info](http://worldtides.info). It is almost free \- I paid $10 for 20,000 one-week retrievals. Even after a ton of debugging and testing, I have only used 220 retrievals. A HTTP get command returns a JSON string with the high and low tide data for 7 days from any location (and time) you want. I store the retrieved data in a file (SPIFFS) so reboots and crashes do not require re-acquisition thereby not using up my credits. Once the data is too old, another 7-days is retrieved. 

## JSON

Parsing JSON is made easy using a library I found: ArduinoJson-v6.19.4.h   
There are newer versions but this seems to work fine. JSON data is retrieved from the web and parsed into an array using this library. The array represents the time of the high and low times. 

### PWM

I pulse the motor on and off to reduce current (thus holding power) when the motor is not moving. Full on, it draws a lot of power and gets hot. By reducing the on-time, it runs cool. It does make a little noise, however.

I “round” the desired position to what I think is the preferred phase. If I don’t, when it lands on other phases, you can hear the PWM more distinctly. So I picked the quietest. The reduction in noise has not been horribly consistent but I think it is better than landing on random phases. 

I did not attempt micro-stepping or half-steps when moving as it seems unnecessary. It could make for a smoother movement, though. The 0.9 degree stepper is fairly jerky in its movements. 

## Console

There is a debug console with limited commands. It is accessible via serial and the web. There is a simple web site allowing access to the console and file transfers to SPIFFS, although I am having weird behaviors with the PC web browser accessing it. It is mainly used to initialize the pointer. For example, if the pointer is currently straight down (step 200\) and you enter:   
200c  
It will reinitialize the current location and move the pointer to the correct location. 

## SPIFFS

SPIFFS (SPI flash file system) is a small file system stored in the onboard flash. It is convenient and works just like it was on SD. On the Thing, there is 4MB total flash. 1.125MB is allocated to program space and 1.75MB to SPIFFS. The other 1.125MB is for OTA programming (not implemented).  

## Sleeping

I originally wanted this to run on a battery which requires turning off the motor and sleeping the processor. The motor randomly jumping to its preferred phase when I powered down made me change my approach. I now drive the motor continuously to hold it in the desired position. 

However untested, now that I rest on what I think is the preferred phase, maybe I can turn off the motor and sleep. This is how projects never really get finished. 

# Next Steps

## Use the hall effect sensor for absolute position

I wonder if a magnet on the pointer can be sensed by the ESP32 on the other side of the face. If so, it would give an absolute position indication as the pointer passed by.

## Is getting tide information necessary?

Other tide clocks on the market implement simple 24 hour 50 minute cycles through the 4 tides. It is desirable for the website to use the data as it shows actual tide levels. However, does the TideOMeter really need to go through that complexity?

## Combine with Thing Plus

There is a Sparkfun Thing Plus hooked up to a BME688 environmental sensor sending data to the IoT server. I think it would be relatively easy to combine both applications. The TideOMeter would end up being the central system for the condo. It could even take over the AIS repeater that sends broadcast and AISHub data from the AIS receiver. 

## Anchoring the boat

Knowing the depth of the water is important when deciding where to anchor and how much chain to put out. Knowing the current tide level and using data from the depth sounder would save you from having to do the mental math of determining the actual depth of the water at low and high tide. 

* You want to make sure that the lowest tide won’t put the boat on the bottom  
* You want to make sure that you have enough scope (length/depth) at high tide  
  * 3:1 is OK for calm conditions and tight anchorages  
  * 5:1 is my preference when we have room  
  * 7:1 or more if we are expecting winds over 20 knots  
* Display the lowest anticipated depth and recommended scopes
